sec.p:
A feasible design of the specimen is defined here as a design, that fulfils the following requirements:


provides a higher torque-carrying capacity in comparison to the disc-shaped specimen;

provides an efficient binding at mandrel–specimen interface and a slippage-free local torsion up to a given level of total deformation;

allows development of an AZFH in the specimen that starts from the bore and penetrates sufficiently in radial direction;

minimizes geometric distortion of the specimen; and

causes solely shearing deformation within AZFH.
